We have reiterated our prior years' audit recommendations that Management:
Require the GSO-Designate to strictly comply with the required physical count of all properties at least once a year using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;
Require the GSO-Designate to maintain Property Cards for all the PPEs of the LGU;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain  Property Ledger Cards and be reconciled with the Property Cards of the GSO-Designate;
Instruct the GSO-Designate to  renew/update the Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs)  every three years after the issuance or whenever there is a change in custodianship to establish proper accountability of LGU properties; and
Direct the GSO-Designate to affix property tags/stickers on all properties of the LGU to facilitate a methodological system of inventory-taking and to strengthen internal control on PPE.
Furthermore, we have recommended that all issued property and equipment with a unit cost below the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00, that are still included in the PPE accounts, be appropriately derecognized from the PPE accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2022-004, dated May 31, 2022, and COA Circular No. 2024-006, dated March 14, 2024.

Instruct the Inventory Committee to prepare an operational plan with clear timelines showing the period to conduct the inventory-taking, the Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Network System, and finally reconcile with the accounting records by January 31, 2026;
Require the Municipal Engineer to spearhead the physical inventory of the road networks because of his technical knowledge and skills in engineering;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and
Require the General Services Officer to maintain a Local Road Inventory, Report of the Local Road Network, and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and their components using the format prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015.

To protect the interest of the LGU from any adverse claim by third parties over government properties, we have recommended that Management:
Direct the OIC-Municipal Assessor, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate, to prepare an action plan on the processing of TCTs over the 12 untitled lots. The following data are required for each lot to be processed:
List of required documents;
Time allotted to gather the documents needed;
Actions to be taken to fast-track the process of land titling;
Budget allocated for land titling;
Status of titling; and
Other necessary details required for the action plan.
Require the Municipal Budget Officer to allocate funds to cover all expenses to cover all expenses to be incurred for land registration as identified in item 1; and
To exhaust all possible means to track all the documents pertaining to the 12 untitled lots owned by the LGU to facilitate the titling of the said real properties.

We have reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendations that the local government unit ensure proper management and accounting of its properties by observing the procedures provided by existing rules and regulations in the custody and management of properties specifically:

Keeping of Property Cards per category of Property, Plant and Equipment by the General Services Officer, Supply Officer or the Local Treasurer, as the case maybe;

Maintaining Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for each category of assets by the Municipal Accountant;

Conducting periodic physical count of all supplies or property of the local government unit and reported on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment as of December 31 of each year to be submitted to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of the following year; and

Maintaining a complete and proper file of Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR) or Property Acknowledgment Receipt (PAR) to identify the whereabouts of the properties as well as the accountable and responsible officers or employees to whom the properties were issued could be readily identified/established.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive to enjoin the compliance of the department heads with COA Circular 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015, to wit:

Create an inventory committee to conduct the physical count and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System.


For the General Services Officer to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components also using the prescribed format as mentioned in the above circular;

For the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network using the prescribed format as mentioned in the above circular and disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Constitute the inventory committee through an order or memorandum that will spearhead the conduct of the One-Time Cleansing of PPEs pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.
Require the Inventory Committee to strictly comply with the required physical count of all properties at least once a year and to submit a copy of the RPCPPE to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;
Require the GSO-Designate to maintain PCs for all the PPEs of the LGU;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain  PPELC and be reconciled with the PCsof the GSO-Designate;
Instruct the GSO-Designate to  renew/update the PARs  every three years after the issuance or whenever there is a change in custodianship to establish proper accountability of LGU properties and to affix property tags/stickers on all properties of the LGU to facilitate a methodological system of inventory-taking and to strengthen internal control on PPE; and
Direct the GSO-Designate to affix property tags/stickers on all properties of the LGU to facilitate a methodological system of inventory-taking and to strengthen internal control of the PPE.
Management signified its willingness to comply with the audit recommendations.

Reconstitute the inventory committee taking into consideration incompatible duties.
Instruct the Inventory Committee to prepare operational plan with clear timelines showing the period to conduct the inventory-taking, the RPCLRN System and finally reconcile with the accounting records by January 31, 2025;
Require the General Services Officer to prepare a RLRN at the end of each accounting period;
Require the Municipal Accountant and GSO to maintain LRNLC and LRNPC for all roads and its components
Require the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map.
Management commented that immediate steps were already undertaken to reconstitute the inventory committee to ensure that proper segregation of duties and responsibilities is observed. Likewise, Management also assured the Audit Team to comply with all other recommendations.

Direct the OIC-Municipal Assessor, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate, to prepare an action plan on the processing of Transfer Certificate of Title over the 83 untitled lots. The following data are required for each lot to be processed, to wit:
List of required documents;
Time allotted to gather the documents needed;
Actions to be taken to fast-track the process of land titling; 
Budget allocated for land titling; 
Status of titling; and 
Other necessary details required for the action plan.
Require the Municipal Budget Officer to allocate funds to cover all expenses to be incurred for land registration as identified in item 1; and
The concerned department heads exhaust all possible means to track all the documents pertaining to the 83 untitled lots owned by the LGU to facilitate the titling of the said real properties.
Management was amenable to the audit observations and signified its willingness to comply with the audit recommendations.

